WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.203
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:08.180
DANIEL LANIGAN: So my
name is Daniel Lanigan.

00:00:08.180 --> 00:00:11.300
I am the CEO and founder of
Lord Hobo Brewing Company,

00:00:11.300 --> 00:00:14.000
as well as a half
dozen other craft beer

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.580
bars over the last 15 years.

00:00:17.580 --> 00:00:21.710
I'm titling this talk today
Lord Hobo Brewing Company

00:00:21.710 --> 00:00:26.659
and the fairytale towards the
first billion dollars, OK?

00:00:26.659 --> 00:00:28.950
I'm going to tell you a little
bit about my background.

00:00:28.950 --> 00:00:30.860
Then we're going to dive
into the brewery itself

00:00:30.860 --> 00:00:32.159
and get into a little
bit of our culture

00:00:32.159 --> 00:00:34.760
and why we're the fastest
growing brewery in the United

00:00:34.760 --> 00:00:36.580
States, I think.

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:39.950
I have some ideas why we are.

00:00:39.950 --> 00:00:41.960
I'm open to other
interpretations.

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:45.010
So briefly, I could speak about
beer and the state of craft

00:00:45.010 --> 00:00:49.490
beer and the nuances of
it and flavor profiles

00:00:49.490 --> 00:00:51.290
and the bubble
bursting and hops,

00:00:51.290 --> 00:00:53.498
and everything else that's
happening in the industry.

00:00:53.498 --> 00:00:55.820
I've been doing this
for my whole adult life.

00:00:55.820 --> 00:00:57.950
I could talk about
this for days.

00:00:57.950 --> 00:00:59.190
We don't have that time.

00:00:59.190 --> 00:01:02.750
So I'm going to try to
slam through a few stories

00:01:02.750 --> 00:01:05.150
and core principles, and
then give you guys some time

00:01:05.150 --> 00:01:07.280
to talk, answer some questions.

00:01:07.280 --> 00:01:11.120
But there's a lot to cover,
and 15 years of my experience

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:14.820
and trying to summarize
that in 27 minutes or less.

00:01:14.820 --> 00:01:20.930
So very quickly, 15 years ago,
I opened up a craft beer bar

00:01:20.930 --> 00:01:23.420
at a college town
at UMass Amherst.

00:01:23.420 --> 00:01:26.690
I was 26, and I
knew that I didn't

00:01:26.690 --> 00:01:28.670
have any skills or
a college degree

00:01:28.670 --> 00:01:31.100
or rich parents
or anything, so I

00:01:31.100 --> 00:01:34.040
had to figure out a way to
develop some long-term income.

00:01:34.040 --> 00:01:36.819
And I didn't want to be
a bartender in my 70s.

00:01:36.819 --> 00:01:38.360
No offense to
70-year-old bartenders,

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:40.200
but I just wanted to
have a way to retire.

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:42.480
And so I wanted to
open up my own place.

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:44.170
I wanted to be my own boss.

00:01:44.170 --> 00:01:47.210
And so I raised up a few
bucks from friends and family,

00:01:47.210 --> 00:01:51.320
sold off all my poetry
books, literally,

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:52.790
and I cobbled
together enough money

00:01:52.790 --> 00:01:57.800
to buy a crappy dive bar on the
outskirts of a college town.

00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:01.400
And I was determined to make
it into a craft beer bar.

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:04.340
And in 2002, there
wasn't a lot of those.

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:07.017
There wasn't a craft beer bar
around Amherst for 100 miles.

00:02:07.017 --> 00:02:08.600
You had to come all
the way to Boston.

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:11.040
And even back then it
was Redbones and Sunset.

00:02:11.040 --> 00:02:12.430
A couple of other stalwarts.

00:02:12.430 --> 00:02:15.540
A place in Albany called
Maharas, which is now gone.

00:02:15.540 --> 00:02:18.050
So at the time, everyone
thought I was crazy,

00:02:18.050 --> 00:02:20.480
because if you know
at UMass Amherst,

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:22.790
it's a pitcher and shot
for a dollar kind of town.

00:02:22.790 --> 00:02:25.400
Every bar caters to
college students.

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:28.010
And there was really nobody
there, fortunately for me,

00:02:28.010 --> 00:02:30.920
catering to adults
and grad students.

00:02:30.920 --> 00:02:35.790
And UMass Amherst area
has a ton of those people.

00:02:35.790 --> 00:02:39.597
So we opened up with $5
pints of 9% IPA and beers

00:02:39.597 --> 00:02:40.930
no one had ever heard of before.

00:02:40.930 --> 00:02:43.890
And fortunately for
me, we got crushed.

00:02:43.890 --> 00:02:46.890
Day 1, place was
packed, and day 2, place

00:02:46.890 --> 00:02:49.460
was packed, and kept
going like that.

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:51.380
And we became sort of
an oasis for people.

00:02:51.380 --> 00:02:53.820
And I think I probably
could have sold Rumple Minze

00:02:53.820 --> 00:02:56.570
and Jagermeister, and we
still would have been packed.

00:02:56.570 --> 00:02:59.319
It's just we were catered
to an older audience, a more

00:02:59.319 --> 00:03:00.860
sophisticated
audience, and there was

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:02.900
just nobody else doing that.

00:03:02.900 --> 00:03:05.310
We just happened to sell
a lot of craft beer,

00:03:05.310 --> 00:03:06.920
and that really worked for us.

00:03:06.920 --> 00:03:09.050
So I was 26.

00:03:09.050 --> 00:03:10.790
I was making more
money than I would ever

00:03:10.790 --> 00:03:12.480
think I would ever
make in my life,

00:03:12.480 --> 00:03:15.554
and I decided to
open another place.

00:03:15.554 --> 00:03:16.970
And that was sort
of a trend I did

00:03:16.970 --> 00:03:19.752
where sort of a serial
entrepreneur at heart,

00:03:19.752 --> 00:03:21.710
and I like to think that
I make good decisions.

00:03:21.710 --> 00:03:23.084
And I say to people
all the time,

00:03:23.084 --> 00:03:26.300
like, the best deals you ever
do are the ones you say no to.

00:03:26.300 --> 00:03:28.430
But I still did some dumb deals.

00:03:28.430 --> 00:03:31.220
And so I opened up a place
Northampton, big restaurant,

00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:33.180
and I went from, like,
working 25 hours a week,

00:03:33.180 --> 00:03:35.270
making tons of money, to
working 80 hours a week

00:03:35.270 --> 00:03:37.850
and making just 10% more money.

00:03:37.850 --> 00:03:40.527
And so it wasn't
a very good idea.

00:03:40.527 --> 00:03:42.860
And I did that for a few
years, and then sold them both.

00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:45.193
I wanted to go back to Boston
and play with the big boys

00:03:45.193 --> 00:03:47.527
and have the craft
beer bar in Boston.

00:03:47.527 --> 00:03:49.610
At the time, the Public
House was getting started,

00:03:49.610 --> 00:03:50.975
Deep Ellum was getting started.

00:03:50.975 --> 00:03:52.850
And I had a lot of
reverence for those places

00:03:52.850 --> 00:03:56.980
and I thought well
in 2006 we won Best

00:03:56.980 --> 00:04:00.030
Beer Bar in the country, But we
were in the middle of nowhere.

00:04:00.030 --> 00:04:02.300
So I sold them all, came
to Boston, determined

00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:05.660
to open up a place, and that's
where we opened up Lord Hobo.

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:09.110
And Lord Hobo turned eight
years old this week on Monday.

00:04:09.110 --> 00:04:11.490
So eight years in the
restaurant business, long time,

00:04:11.490 --> 00:04:13.940
so it's pretty cool to
have that kind of legacy.

00:04:13.940 --> 00:04:16.370
And we actually
feel like we're part

00:04:16.370 --> 00:04:18.714
of the old part of
Cambridge, because I

00:04:18.714 --> 00:04:20.880
feel like since I started
talking a few minutes ago,

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:22.754
there's probably been
two restaurants opening

00:04:22.754 --> 00:04:24.080
in Cambridge.

00:04:24.080 --> 00:04:27.650
So to be able to last that long
and to create sort of a legacy

00:04:27.650 --> 00:04:32.180
has been really important
and fortunate and even lucky.

00:04:32.180 --> 00:04:34.910
So from there, I
opened up a place

00:04:34.910 --> 00:04:37.494
in Baltimore called Alewife, a
place in Queens called Alewife.

00:04:37.494 --> 00:04:39.701
I'm part of a couple other
bars in New York City that

00:04:39.701 --> 00:04:41.150
are all craft beer-focused.

00:04:41.150 --> 00:04:46.150
I have invested in a bar in
Brussels called Moeder Lambic.

00:04:46.150 --> 00:04:48.170
It's probably the
most important--

00:04:48.170 --> 00:04:50.820
arguably the most important
beer bar in all of Europe.

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:56.360
And so craft beer has been
my dominant part of my life,

00:04:56.360 --> 00:04:58.020
for better or worse, you know?

00:04:58.020 --> 00:04:59.050
It's a good lifestyle.

00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:03.170
It's not great for your body.

00:05:03.170 --> 00:05:06.750
There are craft beer bar
owners who are thin, I think.

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:10.630
But I don't know any, you know.

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:12.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:17.647 --> 00:05:18.980
AUDIENCE: Are you drinking that?

00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:19.764
DANIEL LANIGAN: What
the fuck's going on?

00:05:19.764 --> 00:05:20.612
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:20.612 --> 00:05:21.460
Shit.

00:05:21.460 --> 00:05:22.543
I'm not supposed to swear.

00:05:22.543 --> 00:05:24.260
Sorry.

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:26.570
There's an office pool at
the office for how many times

00:05:26.570 --> 00:05:29.490
I say the F word today.

00:05:29.490 --> 00:05:32.300
So I've been paying attention
to the industry for a long time.

00:05:32.300 --> 00:05:33.980
I've been selling
things by hand,

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:37.460
convincing people who are
curious and not convinced,

00:05:37.460 --> 00:05:40.045
and convincing people that craft
beer and the quality of craft

00:05:40.045 --> 00:05:42.579
beer is the way to go.

00:05:42.579 --> 00:05:44.870
And by doing it so passionately
for a really long time,

00:05:44.870 --> 00:05:46.994
and visiting breweries,
and taking staff to Europe,

00:05:46.994 --> 00:05:49.690
and really just pushing
the envelope as hard

00:05:49.690 --> 00:05:52.070
as I could to learn as
much as I could about,

00:05:52.070 --> 00:05:55.660
what is craft beer,
who drinks it, and why?

00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:59.330
And one of our core philosophies
of the brewery is to us,

00:05:59.330 --> 00:06:03.080
beer is the most affordable
luxury item on Earth.

00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:05.390
There's no Saudi prince
that can buy a better

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:06.620
beer than you and I can buy.

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:11.820
The best beers in the world
are $6 or $8, or maybe $10.

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:14.600
Maybe a rare Belgian
bottle is $25 bucks.

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:16.790
But when you do down
on the street, when

00:06:16.790 --> 00:06:18.990
you pay $10 for a
pint at Lord Hobo,

00:06:18.990 --> 00:06:21.140
you're getting a
world-class offering.

00:06:21.140 --> 00:06:24.590
You know, you can't say that
about yachts or wine or even

00:06:24.590 --> 00:06:26.115
steaks or homes
or cars, whatever.

00:06:26.115 --> 00:06:28.490
There's always somebody who
can buy a better one than you

00:06:28.490 --> 00:06:31.680
can buy, except for beer.

00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:35.150
So the difference between
a $4 pint and a $10 pint

00:06:35.150 --> 00:06:37.910
is astronomical in
the sense of value.

00:06:37.910 --> 00:06:40.500
And you can't get that
in any other field.

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:42.860
Even coffee, I think
you can buy coffee beans

00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:46.350
that, like, monkeys shit
through or something like that,

00:06:46.350 --> 00:06:47.960
and it's like $200 a pound.

00:06:47.960 --> 00:06:50.900
So there is a coffee bean that
a Saudi prince can buy that you

00:06:50.900 --> 00:06:51.860
cannot buy.

00:06:51.860 --> 00:06:54.350
But with beer, it's an
affordable luxury item.

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:57.380
So we've been pushing that as
one of our core principles.

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:00.350
So when I was sort of looking
at the landscape of things

00:07:00.350 --> 00:07:02.810
and saying, look, I'm kind
of tired of restaurants,

00:07:02.810 --> 00:07:05.480
the restaurants are not
a real growth industry,

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:08.360
the problem with them is
once your building is full,

00:07:08.360 --> 00:07:09.750
there's no room for growth.

00:07:09.750 --> 00:07:12.140
So if we're slammed
seven nights a week,

00:07:12.140 --> 00:07:14.270
we can't knock down
the walls or go outside

00:07:14.270 --> 00:07:16.711
or go down the street
or go to the next state.

00:07:16.711 --> 00:07:18.210
Unless you want to
open-- unless you

00:07:18.210 --> 00:07:21.602
want to operate 40 restaurants,
which I don't want to do.

00:07:21.602 --> 00:07:23.810
So I thought, I've got to
get into a growth industry.

00:07:23.810 --> 00:07:27.800
I'm watching my friends,
Sam from [INAUDIBLE],, Greg

00:07:27.800 --> 00:07:31.310
from Stone who I met very
early on in my career.

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:34.130
They've worked as
hard as I have.

00:07:34.130 --> 00:07:36.590
Maybe 5% harder, maybe not.

00:07:36.590 --> 00:07:39.914
But they're worth hundreds
of millions of dollars.

00:07:39.914 --> 00:07:41.330
I work just as
hard as those guys,

00:07:41.330 --> 00:07:45.070
and I am not worth a
fraction of 1% of that.

00:07:45.070 --> 00:07:48.630
And so I'm like, what
am I doing wrong here?

00:07:48.630 --> 00:07:51.167
So I looked at the landscape
and thought, at this point--

00:07:51.167 --> 00:07:53.000
this is four years ago
now, so the brewery's

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:54.041
two and a half years old.

00:07:54.041 --> 00:07:57.440
Four years ago I
said, the top 10 IPAs

00:07:57.440 --> 00:08:00.350
in New England that
everyone's going crazy for

00:08:00.350 --> 00:08:03.660
are all commercially unavailable
on a day-to-day basis.

00:08:03.660 --> 00:08:06.650
You've got to know somebody,
wait in line, trade for it,

00:08:06.650 --> 00:08:08.510
paid too much for it on eBay.

00:08:08.510 --> 00:08:10.834
I thought, why is
nobody scaling this?

00:08:10.834 --> 00:08:12.500
If everybody's waiting
in line two hours

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:16.070
for a four-pack
that's $20 bucks,

00:08:16.070 --> 00:08:19.040
why doesn't someone
build a bigger brewery?

00:08:19.040 --> 00:08:21.310
And I thought about
that for a long time,

00:08:21.310 --> 00:08:25.660
and I thought, if somebody
could build world-class IPAs

00:08:25.660 --> 00:08:29.540
and stick them on every
shelf, we would crush it.

00:08:29.540 --> 00:08:32.750
And so that's what
I set out to do.

00:08:32.750 --> 00:08:34.580
I raised a bunch of money.

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:36.169
People like being
part of breweries

00:08:36.169 --> 00:08:37.370
more than they like being
part of restaurants.

00:08:37.370 --> 00:08:39.740
There's something sort of
tactile and sexy and romantic

00:08:39.740 --> 00:08:40.669
about it.

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:43.307
So it was much easier to
raise money for that reason.

00:08:43.307 --> 00:08:45.140
So I raised a bunch of
money, and I went out

00:08:45.140 --> 00:08:46.400
looking for a building.

00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:48.710
And I wanted to be
in Boston proper.

00:08:48.710 --> 00:08:49.490
I'm a Bostonian.

00:08:49.490 --> 00:08:50.531
I'm really proud of that.

00:08:50.531 --> 00:08:52.387
I love the city.

00:08:52.387 --> 00:08:53.970
I've been living
here for a long time.

00:08:53.970 --> 00:08:55.700
I'll always have a home here.

00:08:55.700 --> 00:08:59.400
I couldn't find a building
that suited my needs.

00:08:59.400 --> 00:09:01.970
So I went further afield
and ended up in Woburn.

00:09:01.970 --> 00:09:05.390
And it was my 24th or 25th
building in a 12-month period

00:09:05.390 --> 00:09:06.082
that I saw.

00:09:06.082 --> 00:09:07.790
And I walked in, and
I had to really keep

00:09:07.790 --> 00:09:10.610
a poker face, because I knew
immediately that this was it.

00:09:10.610 --> 00:09:15.000
It was 47,000 square feet,
had tons of infrastructure.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:20.770
It had cranes and vestibules,
bathrooms, fire sprinkler

00:09:20.770 --> 00:09:21.300
systems.

00:09:21.300 --> 00:09:22.620
Things that you
don't think about

00:09:22.620 --> 00:09:24.050
that you end up
having to pay for.

00:09:24.050 --> 00:09:26.570
It just had all the
guts that were there.

00:09:26.570 --> 00:09:28.160
All we needed to do
was add equipment.

00:09:28.160 --> 00:09:31.850
The problem is the rent on
a 47,000-square-foot place--

00:09:31.850 --> 00:09:35.960
even that $7.25 a square foot,
which is a steal relative

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:39.100
to Boston, I was looking at
$65 bucks a foot some places--

00:09:39.100 --> 00:09:43.160
was still $350,000 a year
before taxes and insurance.

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:46.180
So you're looking at
$40,000-plus a month in rent

00:09:46.180 --> 00:09:48.730
for a startup which
has no revenue.

00:09:48.730 --> 00:09:53.030
And on top of that, I
was interviewing a person

00:09:53.030 --> 00:09:54.720
who ended up who is now my COO.

00:09:54.720 --> 00:09:58.430
And he said, man.

00:09:58.430 --> 00:10:02.570
To do what you want to do with
this ambition, you need a team.

00:10:02.570 --> 00:10:05.690
I was like, you don't know
what you're talking about.

00:10:05.690 --> 00:10:08.170
I've been doing all
this stuff myself.

00:10:08.170 --> 00:10:10.330
Well, he was really correct.

00:10:10.330 --> 00:10:11.750
And so we've been carrying--

00:10:11.750 --> 00:10:13.750
you know, we as a startup
brewery, we had a CEO,

00:10:13.750 --> 00:10:17.020
we had a CFO, we had
a CMO, we had an CEO.

00:10:17.020 --> 00:10:18.620
Carrying a lot of
salary for a startup

00:10:18.620 --> 00:10:23.590
brewery that has zero revenue
and $40,000 a month rent due.

00:10:23.590 --> 00:10:25.840
And it took us 12 months
to build the place.

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:27.565
So we had a half
million dollars of rent

00:10:27.565 --> 00:10:30.220
due before we even
opened, plus salaries.

00:10:30.220 --> 00:10:33.490
So it was an ambitious
project for sure,

00:10:33.490 --> 00:10:36.880
and it could have
been a disaster.

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:39.910
Why wasn't it a disaster?

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:41.830
I think it's mostly
because we understood

00:10:41.830 --> 00:10:45.460
what the opportunity was, what
the void in the marketplace

00:10:45.460 --> 00:10:46.360
was.

00:10:46.360 --> 00:10:49.330
We knew that people want
these New England IPAs.

00:10:49.330 --> 00:10:50.770
They want them on every shelf.

00:10:50.770 --> 00:10:51.750
They don't really
want to wait in line.

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:52.583
Some people like it.

00:10:52.583 --> 00:10:54.525
Some people are masochists.

00:10:54.525 --> 00:10:55.400
They like the ritual.

00:10:55.400 --> 00:10:58.180
They like to keep the kids in
the car for two hours crying

00:10:58.180 --> 00:10:59.927
so Dad can get his four-pack.

00:10:59.927 --> 00:11:01.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:01.120 --> 00:11:02.140
I see you out there.

00:11:02.140 --> 00:11:03.415
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:04.690 --> 00:11:06.690
And so we've just filled a void.

00:11:06.690 --> 00:11:12.190
And we opened June 19 of 2015.

00:11:12.190 --> 00:11:17.350
We In our first 12 months, we
sold 9,000 barrels of beer.

00:11:17.350 --> 00:11:18.575
And at that point--

00:11:18.575 --> 00:11:20.200
I think it's still
true-- no one's ever

00:11:20.200 --> 00:11:21.824
sold that much beer
in their first year

00:11:21.824 --> 00:11:23.710
as an independent craft brewery.

00:11:23.710 --> 00:11:28.290
We did 3,000 in '15 total
from June to January 1.

00:11:28.290 --> 00:11:31.320
We did 15,400 last year.

00:11:31.320 --> 00:11:34.630
We'll do about 32,000 this year.

00:11:34.630 --> 00:11:36.580
So to put that in
perspective, there

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:41.290
are roughly 6,000 breweries
in operation in the US,

00:11:41.290 --> 00:11:45.360
and we are just about 100th.

00:11:45.360 --> 00:11:47.920
102, 99, something like that.

00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:50.900
So we leapfrogged
5,900 breweries

00:11:50.900 --> 00:11:53.590
in two and a half years,
which is remarkable.

00:11:53.590 --> 00:11:56.219
By anyone's metric,
it's a massive success.

00:11:56.219 --> 00:11:58.510
And we're all-- there's a
bunch of us in the room here.

00:11:58.510 --> 00:12:01.750
So it's extraordinary
what's happened.

00:12:01.750 --> 00:12:04.510
And we only have four beers.

00:12:04.510 --> 00:12:06.260
And we only have--

00:12:06.260 --> 00:12:09.030
I mean, let me make
sure that's true.

00:12:09.030 --> 00:12:14.030
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:16.030 --> 00:12:18.310
We are now sold in 14 states.

00:12:18.310 --> 00:12:20.530
We just launched
four in eight weeks.

00:12:20.530 --> 00:12:23.200
It was frantic.

00:12:23.200 --> 00:12:27.070
Pretty stupid, but there's a
real sort of a blackout period

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:29.020
for launching around here.

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:31.180
Basically, November,
December, distributors

00:12:31.180 --> 00:12:32.710
don't want to talk to you
because they're all gearing up

00:12:32.710 --> 00:12:33.550
for Christmas.

00:12:33.550 --> 00:12:35.270
January is the slowest
part of the year.

00:12:35.270 --> 00:12:37.270
It's when everyone kind
of catches their breath.

00:12:37.270 --> 00:12:39.120
We didn't want to have
a blackout period.

00:12:39.120 --> 00:12:40.960
We needed to sell more beer.

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:45.920
So we can do about 200,000
barrels in our building.

00:12:45.920 --> 00:12:49.630
I said that before, we'll
do about 32,000 this year.

00:12:49.630 --> 00:12:53.380
We have room to grow 7x
from where we are right now.

00:12:53.380 --> 00:12:57.580
And at some point, you know,
if we approach that capacity,

00:12:57.580 --> 00:12:59.980
we will obviously find another
building, which we just

00:12:59.980 --> 00:13:00.563
did, actually.

00:13:00.563 --> 00:13:05.170
We just bought a building across
the street, 18,000 square feet,

00:13:05.170 --> 00:13:06.370
because it was available.

00:13:06.370 --> 00:13:08.560
I knew that when we
needed it in two years,

00:13:08.560 --> 00:13:09.530
it probably wouldn't
be available,

00:13:09.530 --> 00:13:10.450
so we grabbed it now.

00:13:10.450 --> 00:13:11.950
So we've always
been trying to be

00:13:11.950 --> 00:13:15.240
aggressive with our
opportunity and our capacity.

00:13:15.240 --> 00:13:17.920
And so the typical
brewery constraint,

00:13:17.920 --> 00:13:22.690
we see it literally hundreds and
hundreds of times, is people--

00:13:22.690 --> 00:13:24.020
they don't have enough cash.

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:25.000
They don't have
enough credibility.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:26.374
They don't have
enough customers.

00:13:26.374 --> 00:13:28.270
But they always go too small.

00:13:28.270 --> 00:13:29.880
They go into 4,000 square feet.

00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:32.000
They have a five-barrel system.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.780
To put it in perspective,
we have a 40-barrel.

00:13:34.780 --> 00:13:38.920
So our pots are bigger than a
lot of other breweries' pots.

00:13:38.920 --> 00:13:42.550
And they sell out their
beer, and they don't

00:13:42.550 --> 00:13:43.851
have enough capital to grow.

00:13:43.851 --> 00:13:45.100
They probably still have debt.

00:13:45.100 --> 00:13:46.930
They probably are waiting
for their neighbor

00:13:46.930 --> 00:13:48.305
to go out of
business so they can

00:13:48.305 --> 00:13:50.210
grab another 3,000 square feet.

00:13:50.210 --> 00:13:53.567
So even if you have wild
success and make wonderful beer,

00:13:53.567 --> 00:13:55.150
if you can't grow,
you can't scale it.

00:13:55.150 --> 00:13:57.350
Well, that's not our
motto, obviously.

00:13:57.350 --> 00:13:59.620
Our motto is to go national.

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:07.650
It's working so far.

00:14:07.650 --> 00:14:09.885
Whether or not--

00:14:09.885 --> 00:14:11.510
I have some doubts
about whether or not

00:14:11.510 --> 00:14:14.650
we'll ever see another national
craft brewery, literally

00:14:14.650 --> 00:14:17.000
meaning 40-plus states.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:21.410
Because right now, there's
two or three breweries

00:14:21.410 --> 00:14:24.036
opening a day, and the
hyperlocal movement

00:14:24.036 --> 00:14:25.160
is definitely a real thing.

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:28.334
So the challenge for us--
and it's a fun challenge--

00:14:28.334 --> 00:14:30.500
the challenge of growth,
the challenge of the future

00:14:30.500 --> 00:14:36.530
is, how do we become relevant
as a Boston-based brewery

00:14:36.530 --> 00:14:41.360
to Seattle, or to Portland,
Oregon, or to Vancouver?

00:14:41.360 --> 00:14:43.490
That's the sort of unique
challenge of our future.

00:14:43.490 --> 00:14:46.580
I feel like we'll comfortably
get to 100,000 barrels, which

00:14:46.580 --> 00:14:47.570
is so extraordinary.

00:14:47.570 --> 00:14:51.440
We'd still be the top, I think,
probably 50 or so breweries

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:52.940
in the country.

00:14:52.940 --> 00:14:55.370
But to get to our
capacity and beyond,

00:14:55.370 --> 00:14:58.400
and to get to the
fairytale trail

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:01.135
to the billion
dollar company, we're

00:15:01.135 --> 00:15:02.510
going to have to
figure out a way

00:15:02.510 --> 00:15:05.957
to become relevant to
Seattle, as an example.

00:15:05.957 --> 00:15:07.790
And when they have 200
other breweries there

00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:10.670
that are all making-- well,
most of them making great beer,

00:15:10.670 --> 00:15:12.860
that's the challenge, right?

00:15:12.860 --> 00:15:14.660
How can I get someone
in Seattle to say,

00:15:14.660 --> 00:15:18.140
I'm going to bypass these
125 local breweries to buy

00:15:18.140 --> 00:15:20.480
this brewery from Boston?

00:15:20.480 --> 00:15:21.584
So it's possible.

00:15:21.584 --> 00:15:23.000
I just haven't
figured it out yet.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:24.560
So you guys are all smart.

00:15:24.560 --> 00:15:27.620
Let me know if you
have any ideas.

00:15:27.620 --> 00:15:29.240
We do have a
significant advantage

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:32.314
over a lot of other
breweries nationally,

00:15:32.314 --> 00:15:33.730
which we weren't
really expecting.

00:15:33.730 --> 00:15:36.560
This was not some
clever ploy that we're

00:15:36.560 --> 00:15:38.200
smarter than everybody else.

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:39.810
Just happens to be happening.

00:15:39.810 --> 00:15:48.020
So the New England IPA is a
real now national phenomena.

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:50.360
In the craft beer
circles, everybody

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:55.940
wants or is attempting to make
or is making New England IPA.

00:15:55.940 --> 00:15:58.310
What is New England IPA?

00:15:58.310 --> 00:16:00.540
If anyone in the room
knows that answer,

00:16:00.540 --> 00:16:02.350
you'll probably
be a billionaire.

00:16:02.350 --> 00:16:03.350
What is New England IPA?

00:16:03.350 --> 00:16:04.183
I couldn't tell you.

00:16:04.183 --> 00:16:05.735
It's a pretty random--

00:16:05.735 --> 00:16:07.610
everyone makes them a
little bit differently,

00:16:07.610 --> 00:16:09.140
but they have some similar--

00:16:09.140 --> 00:16:13.310
there are some characters
that are pretty much involved.

00:16:13.310 --> 00:16:15.740
They tend to be hazy,
they tend to be juicy,

00:16:15.740 --> 00:16:18.410
they tend to not have a
lot of residual bitterness.

00:16:18.410 --> 00:16:21.660
They tend to be almost turbid.

00:16:21.660 --> 00:16:23.940
Very tropical, floral aroma.

00:16:23.940 --> 00:16:25.530
And they don't have--

00:16:25.530 --> 00:16:27.960
I mentioned they don't have
a lot of residual bitterness.

00:16:27.960 --> 00:16:31.610
So the West Coast IPA typically
has a lot of malt sweetness

00:16:31.610 --> 00:16:33.760
and a lot of strong bitterness.

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:36.860
The New England IPA is
basically all the good part

00:16:36.860 --> 00:16:39.370
of hops without the sweetness.

00:16:39.370 --> 00:16:43.950
And so The Alchemist,
Hill Farmstead, Trillium,

00:16:43.950 --> 00:16:47.360
Tree House, Lawson's,
Fiddlehead, Maine,

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:51.350
et cetera, all those
folks make what I would

00:16:51.350 --> 00:16:53.300
consider New England-style IPA.

00:16:53.300 --> 00:16:55.640
They just don't make them
to leave New England.

00:16:55.640 --> 00:16:57.830
They make them to stay
within sometimes 30 miles

00:16:57.830 --> 00:16:59.980
of their home brewery.

00:16:59.980 --> 00:17:03.710
Trillium sells 15,000 barrels
a year out their front door.

00:17:03.710 --> 00:17:05.480
It's incredible.

00:17:05.480 --> 00:17:08.119
Tree House is on pace to
sell 25,000 barrels out

00:17:08.119 --> 00:17:10.760
of their new facility
at their front door.

00:17:10.760 --> 00:17:12.530
Crazy talk.

00:17:12.530 --> 00:17:17.000
So we didn't have the benefit
of baking the pie that long.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.690
We couldn't take seven years to
become Tree House or Trillium

00:17:20.690 --> 00:17:22.150
like they have.

00:17:22.150 --> 00:17:25.050
I think trillium's
five years old.

00:17:25.050 --> 00:17:26.520
We had to do it in a hurry.

00:17:26.520 --> 00:17:28.430
But the benefit
of that for us is

00:17:28.430 --> 00:17:34.580
right now, California, Oregon,
Washington, UK, Australia,

00:17:34.580 --> 00:17:36.620
they want New England
IPA, and we are literally

00:17:36.620 --> 00:17:40.220
the only brewery that's scaling
and can actually get the beer

00:17:40.220 --> 00:17:43.270
to them fresh and beautiful.

00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:46.050
And we get to be first and
we get to define the style,

00:17:46.050 --> 00:17:47.800
because there's a lot
of other breweries--

00:17:47.800 --> 00:17:49.758
like, there's a million
breweries in California

00:17:49.758 --> 00:17:51.720
now finally making
New England-style IPA.

00:17:51.720 --> 00:17:54.370
But they're not the same
as what we're doing here,

00:17:54.370 --> 00:17:56.510
because they're
getting typically beers

00:17:56.510 --> 00:17:58.374
that have been traded or sold.

00:17:58.374 --> 00:17:59.540
Maybe they're six weeks old.

00:17:59.540 --> 00:18:00.590
Maybe they're 12 weeks old.

00:18:00.590 --> 00:18:01.881
Maybe they're totally oxidized.

00:18:01.881 --> 00:18:03.890
Maybe they're not
in great shape.

00:18:03.890 --> 00:18:05.570
And maybe they're
having a hard time

00:18:05.570 --> 00:18:08.630
dealing with that yeast strain
that's particular to our style,

00:18:08.630 --> 00:18:09.940
or whatever the reason is.

00:18:09.940 --> 00:18:11.690
There's not a lot of
breweries on the West

00:18:11.690 --> 00:18:15.170
Coast doing New England-style
IPAs with great success.

00:18:15.170 --> 00:18:17.210
We kind of have that
market cornered.

00:18:17.210 --> 00:18:21.290
And yet we are the only ones to
be able to produce it at scale.

00:18:21.290 --> 00:18:24.052
So fortunately for
us, we're first.

00:18:24.052 --> 00:18:25.760
Not only are we first,
but there's really

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:27.956
nobody on our heels.

00:18:27.956 --> 00:18:29.330
I can't see anybody
in the market

00:18:29.330 --> 00:18:32.210
right now that's about to
scale up significantly,

00:18:32.210 --> 00:18:34.850
and who will come into the
market and challenge us.

00:18:34.850 --> 00:18:37.520
So we have this really
interesting sweet spot

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:41.580
of opportunity that I
couldn't have predicted.

00:18:41.580 --> 00:18:45.190
So we are really
strong in that way.

00:18:45.190 --> 00:18:47.249
Any questions so far?

00:18:47.249 --> 00:18:48.290
AUDIENCE: Quick question.

00:18:48.290 --> 00:18:52.590
So I guess I just don't have
kind of a good feel for what

00:18:52.590 --> 00:18:53.736
distinguishes [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:56.670 --> 00:19:00.180
DANIEL LANIGAN: The question
was about this gentleman likes

00:19:00.180 --> 00:19:02.352
Green Flash West Coast
IPA and he drinks our beer

00:19:02.352 --> 00:19:03.810
and likes that as
well, but doesn't

00:19:03.810 --> 00:19:05.500
notice a lot of difference.

00:19:05.500 --> 00:19:08.020
And I will say there's
a lot of difference.

00:19:08.020 --> 00:19:11.350
And I think it has any
drunk side by side and not

00:19:11.350 --> 00:19:11.850
in a vacuum.

00:19:11.850 --> 00:19:13.560
Because to me, Green
Flash West Coast

00:19:13.560 --> 00:19:18.180
is incredibly bitter and very
malty and very sticky and sweet

00:19:18.180 --> 00:19:20.310
and almost cloyingly so.

00:19:20.310 --> 00:19:22.140
And so it's still enjoyable.

00:19:22.140 --> 00:19:24.545
I've drank a million Green
Flash West Coast IPAs.

00:19:24.545 --> 00:19:25.920
I tend not to
drink them anymore,

00:19:25.920 --> 00:19:27.510
because I've gotten
tired of that sort

00:19:27.510 --> 00:19:29.839
of cloying sweetness and
that really harsh bitterness.

00:19:29.839 --> 00:19:31.630
I like the beer to be
softer, more elegant.

00:19:31.630 --> 00:19:35.154
So our beers are deliberately
lower carbonated, for example.

00:19:35.154 --> 00:19:37.070
You don't get a lot of
carbonic bite up front.

00:19:37.070 --> 00:19:39.510
To me, carbonic bite gets
in the way of flavor.

00:19:39.510 --> 00:19:42.590
So the reason why you
can't chug a Coca-Cola

00:19:42.590 --> 00:19:44.660
is because the
carbonation's so high.

00:19:44.660 --> 00:19:46.545
But if you ever had
a flat Coca-Cola,

00:19:46.545 --> 00:19:48.450
you could crush it, right?

00:19:48.450 --> 00:19:49.762
Our beers are lower--

00:19:49.762 --> 00:19:51.220
not that you would
want to, really.

00:19:51.220 --> 00:19:53.505
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:54.420 --> 00:19:55.710
So our beers are--

00:19:55.710 --> 00:19:58.595
so most breweries, they
package their cans at 2.8 PSI.

00:19:58.595 --> 00:19:59.550
Our is 2.5, right?

00:19:59.550 --> 00:20:01.560
So it's about a 12%,
a 13% difference.

00:20:01.560 --> 00:20:04.200
So I think that's a
noticeable difference

00:20:04.200 --> 00:20:05.775
so that what you
get with our beer

00:20:05.775 --> 00:20:07.830
is just smooth
flavor right away.

00:20:07.830 --> 00:20:09.670
Elegant, subtle,
balanced flavor.

00:20:09.670 --> 00:20:12.400
Whereas Green Flash,
to me, I have that,

00:20:12.400 --> 00:20:15.360
I get tons of carbonation,
which blinds me from the flavor.

00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:16.622
I have to wait for it.

00:20:16.622 --> 00:20:19.080
I have to let my mouth kind of
get over the assault it just

00:20:19.080 --> 00:20:20.890
had and get into the flavor.

00:20:20.890 --> 00:20:24.510
So if you had 10 West
Coast IPAs that are famous

00:20:24.510 --> 00:20:26.910
and 10 East Coast
IPAs that are famous,

00:20:26.910 --> 00:20:29.410
you would really see
a huge difference.

00:20:29.410 --> 00:20:32.130
AUDIENCE: So in terms of sort
of craft beers that have scaled,

00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:34.230
you know, there's some
sort of obvious analogies.

00:20:34.230 --> 00:20:38.160
You know, Boston Beer Company,
Anchor, maybe Dogfish, you

00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:41.100
know, behind that, how do
you compare those models?

00:20:41.100 --> 00:20:44.550
DANIEL LANIGAN: Well, Boston
Beer, they are geniuses.

00:20:44.550 --> 00:20:47.640
They've never owned their own
brewery until this little 10

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:49.860
brewery in Jamaica Plain.

00:20:49.860 --> 00:20:51.450
They have contract-brewed
their beer

00:20:51.450 --> 00:20:54.400
in Cincinnati for 30 years.

00:20:54.400 --> 00:20:55.740
He's a marketing genius.

00:20:55.740 --> 00:20:57.859
They have 63 flavors.

00:20:57.859 --> 00:20:58.650
He's a billionaire.

00:20:58.650 --> 00:21:00.233
They're a multibillion
dollar company.

00:21:00.233 --> 00:21:01.300
They're publicly traded.

00:21:01.300 --> 00:21:03.050
You know the story there.

00:21:03.050 --> 00:21:04.920
Absolute genius.

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:06.990
He was on TV in the
'80s, telling us--

00:21:06.990 --> 00:21:11.940
you know, a kid cooking beer
on his kitchen stove, saying,

00:21:11.940 --> 00:21:16.010
the big guys spill more beer
today that I brew in a year.

00:21:16.010 --> 00:21:17.490
And that was true back then.

00:21:17.490 --> 00:21:20.620
And now he's the big
guy, which is amazing.

00:21:20.620 --> 00:21:22.180
So good for him.

00:21:22.180 --> 00:21:26.490
Dogfish Head-- so Sam Adams
does 2.7 million barrels a year.

00:21:26.490 --> 00:21:29.130
Dogfish Head does about 300,000.

00:21:29.130 --> 00:21:32.040
And so Stone does about
360,000, Bell's is 400,00.

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:37.900
So those are the big guys
in the craft world now.

00:21:37.900 --> 00:21:39.530
New Belgium does a million.

00:21:39.530 --> 00:21:41.850
Sierra Nevada does
just over a million.

00:21:41.850 --> 00:21:46.950
So it's no guarantee for us
to get to 100,000 or 200,000

00:21:46.950 --> 00:21:51.760
because we are then becoming
a big boy in a very real way.

00:21:51.760 --> 00:21:54.780
So Dogfish Head has
never before experienced

00:21:54.780 --> 00:21:55.950
non-double digit growth.

00:21:55.950 --> 00:21:57.780
It's always been
greater than 10%.

00:21:57.780 --> 00:22:00.612
A lot of times, much bigger
than-- greater than 10%.

00:22:00.612 --> 00:22:02.070
This is the first
year or last year

00:22:02.070 --> 00:22:04.440
where they were single digits.

00:22:04.440 --> 00:22:08.100
And Sierra Nevada took a
step back at 6% last year.

00:22:08.100 --> 00:22:10.920
First year ever they
lost some market share

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:12.330
instead of growing.

00:22:12.330 --> 00:22:16.350
So I look at that
challenge earlier

00:22:16.350 --> 00:22:20.610
being relevant on a national
level when you're in California

00:22:20.610 --> 00:22:22.835
and I'm drinking in Boston.

00:22:22.835 --> 00:22:24.960
That's the challenge that
those guys are facing now

00:22:24.960 --> 00:22:28.590
and the challenges that I'm
concerned about in the future.

