So walking through,
taking a tour here

00:23:03.510 --> 00:23:08.940
and looking at our office
space versus your office space,

00:23:08.940 --> 00:23:14.430
for example, you know, if it
was Larry and Sergey's brewing

00:23:14.430 --> 00:23:16.267
company all those
years ago, I'd be

00:23:16.267 --> 00:23:18.600
curious to see what their
office space would looks like.

00:23:18.600 --> 00:23:20.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:20.320 --> 00:23:22.320
AUDIENCE: It would look
like yours now probably.

00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:23.220
[LAUGH]

00:23:23.220 --> 00:23:27.840
DANIEL LANIGAN: So we operate at
sort of two trains running side

00:23:27.840 --> 00:23:30.645
by side, and one of them is
a relatively mature train,

00:23:30.645 --> 00:23:32.810
and one of them is
relatively a startup.

00:23:32.810 --> 00:23:35.280
You know, we're two
and a half years old.

00:23:35.280 --> 00:23:37.770
Four years ago, I moved
into that massive facility

00:23:37.770 --> 00:23:40.570
with me and my dog and
a little broken desk

00:23:40.570 --> 00:23:42.960
and a crappy Wi-Fi signal,
and that was it, you know?

00:23:42.960 --> 00:23:47.160
And now we have 65 employees and
we'll do $25 million of revenue

00:23:47.160 --> 00:23:47.830
next year.

00:23:47.830 --> 00:23:49.750
And we're really just
getting started, right?

00:23:49.750 --> 00:23:53.099
So there's so much
to learn, and there's

00:23:53.099 --> 00:23:54.390
so many ways to do this, right?

00:23:54.390 --> 00:23:59.370
So the model that The
Alchemist uses or Trillium uses

00:23:59.370 --> 00:24:00.670
is wildly successful.

00:24:00.670 --> 00:24:03.106
You know, Trillium prints cash.

00:24:03.106 --> 00:24:04.980
They just don't have a
scalable model, right?

00:24:04.980 --> 00:24:07.200
So they're probably
making more money

00:24:07.200 --> 00:24:10.900
than they ever dreamed about,
and they're probably really,

00:24:10.900 --> 00:24:13.290
really happy people.

00:24:13.290 --> 00:24:15.780
I wouldn't-- I'm just not
personally satisfied with that.

00:24:15.780 --> 00:24:18.029
We're constantly trying to
innovate and be thoughtful,

00:24:18.029 --> 00:24:20.540
and we have a lot of
transparency and openness.

00:24:20.540 --> 00:24:23.070
And sometimes it's a
little bit too democratic.

00:24:23.070 --> 00:24:24.800
Sometimes there just
needs to be someone

00:24:24.800 --> 00:24:26.820
calling the shots sometimes.

00:24:26.820 --> 00:24:30.670
But for the most part, we
lean on other companies

00:24:30.670 --> 00:24:31.950
and how they do things well.

00:24:31.950 --> 00:24:34.580
And we also learn from
a lot of companies,

00:24:34.580 --> 00:24:36.180
how they do things poorly.

00:24:36.180 --> 00:24:38.140
And I love to learn
from people's mistakes.

00:24:38.140 --> 00:24:39.420
I don't want to make any.

00:24:39.420 --> 00:24:42.450
And thus far as a
four-year-old company,

00:24:42.450 --> 00:24:44.940
I don't think we've made
any glaring mistakes.

00:24:44.940 --> 00:24:46.865
And I'm sure I'll bite--

00:24:46.865 --> 00:24:50.750
eat those words
soon, but so far,

00:24:50.750 --> 00:24:52.370
we have a lot of smart people.

00:24:52.370 --> 00:24:54.120
You know, we have a
lot of people that are

00:24:54.120 --> 00:24:56.520
good at things I'm not good at.

00:24:56.520 --> 00:25:00.300
I am pretty self-aware,
and I don't like to mess

00:25:00.300 --> 00:25:01.850
around with things
I'm not good at.

00:25:01.850 --> 00:25:02.820
So if I'm not good
at something, I just

00:25:02.820 --> 00:25:04.840
hire somebody who's
better than me at it,

00:25:04.840 --> 00:25:06.390
and let them take
the reins on that.

00:25:06.390 --> 00:25:09.860
So I used to wear 74 hats.

00:25:09.860 --> 00:25:12.030
Then it was 30,
and then it was 12.

00:25:12.030 --> 00:25:16.470
And now I'm just steering
the big battleship.

00:25:16.470 --> 00:25:18.810
I've got a lot of people
doing really important things,

00:25:18.810 --> 00:25:20.070
working side by side with me.

00:25:20.070 --> 00:25:21.820
AUDIENCE: Can I ask
you one more question?

00:25:21.820 --> 00:25:23.010
DANIEL LANIGAN: Sure.

00:25:23.010 --> 00:25:24.468
AUDIENCE: I think
you said that you

00:25:24.468 --> 00:25:25.718
started this when you were 26.

00:25:25.718 --> 00:25:27.717
DANIEL LANIGAN: I started
in the industry at 26.

00:25:27.717 --> 00:25:28.390
AUDIENCE: At 26.

00:25:28.390 --> 00:25:29.640
Yeah.

00:25:29.640 --> 00:25:32.100
And you didn't
graduate from college?

00:25:32.100 --> 00:25:34.032
DANIEL LANIGAN: I did not.

00:25:34.032 --> 00:25:36.570
AUDIENCE: What were you going
through between 20 and 26,

00:25:36.570 --> 00:25:38.652
and how did you--

00:25:38.652 --> 00:25:40.485
what kind of gave you
the inspiration that--

00:25:40.485 --> 00:25:40.800
I mean--

00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:42.591
DANIEL LANIGAN: Piles
of cocaine, you know?

00:25:42.591 --> 00:25:44.416
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:44.416 --> 00:25:45.540
AUDIENCE: This is recorded.

00:25:45.540 --> 00:25:46.698
You understand that?

00:25:46.698 --> 00:25:48.450
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:49.240 --> 00:25:50.350
OK.

00:25:50.350 --> 00:25:52.560
What were you going through
physically on the table?

00:25:52.560 --> 00:25:53.768
DANIEL LANIGAN: I understand.

00:25:53.768 --> 00:25:54.870
I understand.

00:25:54.870 --> 00:25:55.740
Literally piles.

00:25:55.740 --> 00:25:58.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:58.830 --> 00:26:00.730
From 20 to 20-- so I
dropped out of school.

00:26:00.730 --> 00:26:01.830
I went to Northeastern
for a year.

00:26:01.830 --> 00:26:02.955
I wasn't ready for college.

00:26:02.955 --> 00:26:03.660
I dropped out.

00:26:03.660 --> 00:26:04.710
And I worked in Boston.

00:26:04.710 --> 00:26:05.430
I was a courier.

00:26:05.430 --> 00:26:07.140
I worked at cafes.

00:26:07.140 --> 00:26:10.350
And I was adamant
about traveling.

00:26:10.350 --> 00:26:12.560
And I'd had a day that
changed my life forever.

00:26:12.560 --> 00:26:13.600
I met Allen Ginsberg.

00:26:13.600 --> 00:26:15.600
I went to a reading at
the Boston Public Library

00:26:15.600 --> 00:26:18.390
when I was 19, and that changed
my life completely forever.

00:26:18.390 --> 00:26:19.894
And I was obsessed
with literature

00:26:19.894 --> 00:26:22.560
and reading and traveling, and I
got really into the beat stuff.

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:25.020
And I ended up moving to Mexico.

00:26:25.020 --> 00:26:28.850
I lived in San Cristobal de
las Casas for eight months

00:26:28.850 --> 00:26:31.260
because I could afford to
live there and be an artist.

00:26:31.260 --> 00:26:33.080
I was writing and reading.

00:26:33.080 --> 00:26:35.310
I was literally, like,
reading Shakespeare all day

00:26:35.310 --> 00:26:39.100
and then going to the cafe,
and then drinking 17 beers,

00:26:39.100 --> 00:26:41.600
and then going back.

00:26:41.600 --> 00:26:43.980
So I was mostly just traveling
and working to travel,

00:26:43.980 --> 00:26:45.320
traveling to work.

00:26:45.320 --> 00:26:47.910
Working 80 hours a week and
then saving up $3,000 grand.

00:26:47.910 --> 00:26:50.990
Then going off for six months
and staying in hostels,

00:26:50.990 --> 00:26:52.910
and that sort of thing.

00:26:52.910 --> 00:26:56.110
It was an incredible lifestyle.

00:26:56.110 --> 00:27:00.470
Every day was vibrant and
alive and euphoric and super

00:27:00.470 --> 00:27:03.260
exciting and optimistic.

00:27:03.260 --> 00:27:05.270
And I got really
freaked out that I

00:27:05.270 --> 00:27:08.180
had no money and no income
and no skill set and no future

00:27:08.180 --> 00:27:09.300
and no one to pay for me.

00:27:09.300 --> 00:27:12.467
So I had to open a business.

00:27:12.467 --> 00:27:14.550
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
being relevant in Seattle.

00:27:14.550 --> 00:27:15.674
What about internationally?

00:27:15.674 --> 00:27:18.240
I feel like American beer is
probably the best in the world

00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:20.850
now, whereas like 20
years ago, it wasn't.

00:27:20.850 --> 00:27:24.060
But if I go to Europe now,
the beer's not as good.

00:27:24.060 --> 00:27:27.029
So are you thinking about sort
of international expansion?

00:27:27.029 --> 00:27:28.070
DANIEL LANIGAN: For sure.

00:27:28.070 --> 00:27:29.840
Why would I expand
in the US when

00:27:29.840 --> 00:27:32.347
there's three different
breweries opening a day?

00:27:32.347 --> 00:27:34.430
Why wouldn't I go somewhere
else where there's not

00:27:34.430 --> 00:27:36.060
a lot of competition?

00:27:36.060 --> 00:27:39.380
So we're looking
squarely at Australia.

00:27:39.380 --> 00:27:41.630
I'm going to
Australia in January

00:27:41.630 --> 00:27:43.610
with the goal of doing
some significant vetting

00:27:43.610 --> 00:27:47.510
and seeing if we can actually
physically open up a monster

00:27:47.510 --> 00:27:50.015
facility there and try to
become the American craft

00:27:50.015 --> 00:27:51.290
brewery of Australia.

00:27:51.290 --> 00:27:53.600
It's English speaking and
there's 22 million people.

00:27:53.600 --> 00:27:56.150
They drink a lot
of beer per capita.

00:27:56.150 --> 00:27:57.890
They spend a lot
of money on beer.

00:27:57.890 --> 00:28:01.290
A six-pack of Brooklyn
lager in Australia is $38.

00:28:01.290 --> 00:28:04.549
So we're looking to ship beer
there as soon as possible.

00:28:04.549 --> 00:28:05.840
Get some testers in the market.

00:28:05.840 --> 00:28:07.660
And it's halfway
around the world,

00:28:07.660 --> 00:28:09.780
and it's expensive and
difficult logistically,

00:28:09.780 --> 00:28:15.290
but it's an open terrain in a
way that the US market is not.

00:28:15.290 --> 00:28:17.745
AUDIENCE: I would imagine
that you are, especially

00:28:17.745 --> 00:28:19.370
with your business
model, you're really

00:28:19.370 --> 00:28:21.520
dependent on distributors.

00:28:21.520 --> 00:28:26.480
And you know, alcohol
distributors in Massachusetts

00:28:26.480 --> 00:28:28.370
are legendarily powerful.

00:28:28.370 --> 00:28:33.110
We hear a lot about pay to
play and all kinds of problems

00:28:33.110 --> 00:28:34.850
people have had with them.

00:28:34.850 --> 00:28:36.980
Now you're dealing
presumably with distributors

00:28:36.980 --> 00:28:39.590
in other states as well, so
you're getting, I would assume,

00:28:39.590 --> 00:28:43.580
a really good perspective on
the whole distributor scene.

00:28:43.580 --> 00:28:45.770
I'm wondering what
you can tell us

00:28:45.770 --> 00:28:48.380
in public here about the
challenges, shall we say,

00:28:48.380 --> 00:28:50.960
of working with distributors.

00:28:50.960 --> 00:28:52.500
How do you do it?

00:28:52.500 --> 00:28:56.100
How do you get your space with
all the competition out there?

00:28:56.100 --> 00:28:59.272
What's it like to do that?

00:28:59.272 --> 00:29:00.980
DANIEL LANIGAN: That's
a loaded question.

00:29:00.980 --> 00:29:02.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:02.290 --> 00:29:04.010
How much time do we have?

00:29:04.010 --> 00:29:08.270
Distributors are a necessary
part of the growth process.

00:29:08.270 --> 00:29:10.800
The partnerships are
really important to us.

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:13.514
We do a tremendous amount
of vetting and research,

00:29:13.514 --> 00:29:14.930
and we have a lot
of other friends

00:29:14.930 --> 00:29:17.060
who own breweries who have
distributed it with those folks

00:29:17.060 --> 00:29:17.750
previously.

00:29:17.750 --> 00:29:21.790
So it's pretty easy these
days to find a good one.

00:29:21.790 --> 00:29:26.005
Or the best of the worst, if
you want to look at it that way.

00:29:26.005 --> 00:29:27.380
If you want to
make a whole bunch

00:29:27.380 --> 00:29:29.377
of bloodless money,
passionless money,

00:29:29.377 --> 00:29:30.460
you open up a distributor.

00:29:30.460 --> 00:29:31.640
It's great.

00:29:31.640 --> 00:29:35.079
You're just a glorified
delivery service,

00:29:35.079 --> 00:29:36.620
and the margins are
insane, you know?

00:29:36.620 --> 00:29:37.760
So good for them.

00:29:37.760 --> 00:29:41.175
And we have no
control over that.

00:29:41.175 --> 00:29:43.550
We have a few distributor
partners in the room right now.

00:29:43.550 --> 00:29:44.050
And--

00:29:44.050 --> 00:29:45.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:45.630 --> 00:29:49.300
Yeah, their faces went
white once I said that.

00:29:49.300 --> 00:29:51.060
And so they charge
a massive market,

00:29:51.060 --> 00:29:53.240
but they also have a lot
of costs that we don't see.

00:29:53.240 --> 00:29:56.300
So they're a necessary
part of growth for sure

00:29:56.300 --> 00:29:58.460
for us especially,
because we don't

00:29:58.460 --> 00:30:03.276
have the luxury of waiting
to build a unicorn that

00:30:03.276 --> 00:30:05.900
sort of bakes long enough where
people want to come to our door

00:30:05.900 --> 00:30:07.460
and wait all day for beer.

00:30:07.460 --> 00:30:09.380
So we need to grow,
and so we need

00:30:09.380 --> 00:30:11.480
to make good decisions
about our partnerships.

00:30:11.480 --> 00:30:14.450
And we have great
partners, truly.

00:30:14.450 --> 00:30:17.000
We have some-- like I said,
some in the room right now.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:18.350
We

00:30:18.350 --> 00:30:21.860
Today was our ABP, which
is our Annual Budget

00:30:21.860 --> 00:30:25.820
Planning, I think, with our
distributor in New York State.

00:30:25.820 --> 00:30:27.695
So we just beat each
other up for four hours,

00:30:27.695 --> 00:30:30.195
and now we're going to have a
beer, and we'll figure it out.

00:30:30.195 --> 00:30:31.370
And then we're like, hey.

00:30:31.370 --> 00:30:32.120
Sell more beer.

00:30:32.120 --> 00:30:32.995
And they're like, no.

00:30:32.995 --> 00:30:34.345
No, you-- no, no.

00:30:34.345 --> 00:30:36.320
And then we fight about
margin and we fight

00:30:36.320 --> 00:30:39.140
about spend and investment.

00:30:39.140 --> 00:30:41.784
And the end of the day, the
real problem ultimately-- you're

00:30:41.784 --> 00:30:43.200
talking about the
power struggle--

00:30:43.200 --> 00:30:46.380
is that they have franchise
law in their favor.

00:30:46.380 --> 00:30:48.530
So in order for us to
leave them if we're

00:30:48.530 --> 00:30:51.770
dissatisfied with their
service, it's very prohibitive.

00:30:51.770 --> 00:30:54.750
And that's really the
crux of that issue.

00:30:54.750 --> 00:30:57.830
But as far as pay
to play and whatnot,

00:30:57.830 --> 00:31:00.260
I feel strongly that
if you make great beer,

00:31:00.260 --> 00:31:02.149
you're not going
to get replaced.

00:31:02.149 --> 00:31:04.190
The people that are
complaining about pay to play

00:31:04.190 --> 00:31:05.934
is because they
make shitty beer,

00:31:05.934 --> 00:31:07.850
and someone came in and
took their draft line,

00:31:07.850 --> 00:31:09.710
took their spot on the shelf.

00:31:09.710 --> 00:31:12.110
So if you do your
job right, like,

00:31:12.110 --> 00:31:13.950
we don't really worry
about anybody else.

00:31:13.950 --> 00:31:16.370
There's enough room in Mass
for all these breweries

00:31:16.370 --> 00:31:19.200
to triple in size and crush it
and for us to still do really

00:31:19.200 --> 00:31:19.700
well.

00:31:22.970 --> 00:31:26.120
Craft brewing in general is
13% of the overall consumption

00:31:26.120 --> 00:31:28.910
of domestic products in the
United States and only 17%

00:31:28.910 --> 00:31:30.950
of dollars.

00:31:30.950 --> 00:31:34.370
We're 0.0001% of that 13%.

00:31:34.370 --> 00:31:38.630
So for us to double, there's
enough room for 50 or 60

00:31:38.630 --> 00:31:42.630
or 100 breweries of our size
to also double and to still

00:31:42.630 --> 00:31:45.310
crush it, because we're such
a small piece of the big pie.

00:31:45.310 --> 00:31:48.880
So I don't get too
caught up in that stuff,

00:31:48.880 --> 00:31:52.367
because we're just focusing
on doing our job really well,

00:31:52.367 --> 00:31:54.700
and we want to be the best
partner that that distributor

00:31:54.700 --> 00:31:56.380
has, period.

00:31:56.380 --> 00:32:00.220
Our goal is, how do we get
Remarkable Liquids in New York

00:32:00.220 --> 00:32:05.020
State to love us 1%, 10%, 100%
more than they love anybody

00:32:05.020 --> 00:32:06.310
else in their portfolio?

00:32:06.310 --> 00:32:07.459
That's our job.

00:32:07.459 --> 00:32:08.500
We want to be profitable.

00:32:08.500 --> 00:32:09.370
We want to be fresh.

00:32:09.370 --> 00:32:11.578
We want to say, when the
beer's available for pickup,

00:32:11.578 --> 00:32:12.880
it's actually there.

00:32:12.880 --> 00:32:16.250
These guys send trucks to
places, and it's like, oops.

00:32:16.250 --> 00:32:17.560
We're not ready for you.

00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:18.680
Simple stuff like that.

00:32:18.680 --> 00:32:21.880
So our job is we take
care of our own house.

00:32:21.880 --> 00:32:23.210
we're going to be just fine.

00:32:23.210 --> 00:32:27.790
AUDIENCE: So you attribute
a lot of your early growth

00:32:27.790 --> 00:32:32.760
or quick growth to
picking a larger floor

00:32:32.760 --> 00:32:37.780
space than a normal new
craft brewer might do.

00:32:37.780 --> 00:32:41.590
So then why did you choose
to do that in Boston

00:32:41.590 --> 00:32:44.524
and not somewhere that
has much cheaper rent?

00:32:44.524 --> 00:32:45.940
DANIEL LANIGAN: I
didn't say I was

00:32:45.940 --> 00:32:47.148
the smartest guy in the room.

00:32:47.148 --> 00:32:48.304
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:49.650 --> 00:32:51.940
Because I have a lot of
Boston pride, and that's

00:32:51.940 --> 00:32:52.670
important to me.

00:32:52.670 --> 00:32:54.790
I think if it was
just a money play,

00:32:54.790 --> 00:32:56.860
it was just a growth
play, we could have

00:32:56.860 --> 00:32:59.260
done this many other places.

00:32:59.260 --> 00:33:00.860
But our location is wonderful.

00:33:00.860 --> 00:33:03.070
We're right in the
corner of 93 and 95.

00:33:03.070 --> 00:33:07.100
It's the busiest intersection
of cars in all the Northeast.

00:33:07.100 --> 00:33:09.230
We have several hundred
thousand cars driving

00:33:09.230 --> 00:33:11.170
within a mile of us every day.

00:33:11.170 --> 00:33:12.490
We have 100 parking spots.

00:33:12.490 --> 00:33:15.060
We had 50,000 square feet,
now 18,000 more square feet

00:33:15.060 --> 00:33:16.120
across the street.

00:33:16.120 --> 00:33:19.930
So strategically, location-wise
for truck access and access

00:33:19.930 --> 00:33:23.660
to the city and a
talent pool also,

00:33:23.660 --> 00:33:25.890
like, we want to
pull smart people.

00:33:25.890 --> 00:33:27.700
You know, if I'm in
the middle of Vermont

00:33:27.700 --> 00:33:30.030
because I want cheap rent,
maybe the talent pool

00:33:30.030 --> 00:33:31.720
isn't as strong as it is here.

00:33:31.720 --> 00:33:33.430
There's a whole
bunch of factors,

00:33:33.430 --> 00:33:35.800
but mostly its proximity
to where I live.

00:33:35.800 --> 00:33:37.510
I live in the Seaport.

00:33:37.510 --> 00:33:38.710
I have a reverse commute.

00:33:38.710 --> 00:33:41.376
I drive north when everyone else
is going south, and vise versa.

00:33:41.376 --> 00:33:43.040
So I've grown to love Woburn.

00:33:43.040 --> 00:33:45.220
And I love our location,
and I love our building,

00:33:45.220 --> 00:33:47.690
and I wouldn't go anywhere else.

00:33:47.690 --> 00:33:49.180
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:33:49.180 --> 00:33:51.430
AUDIENCE: So you've said how
there's so many breweries

00:33:51.430 --> 00:33:53.980
opening every day, and there's
so much room for all of you

00:33:53.980 --> 00:33:54.910
to expand.

00:33:54.910 --> 00:33:57.370
Do you think that's
a sustainable growth?

00:33:57.370 --> 00:33:59.170
And in your opinion,
like, where do you

00:33:59.170 --> 00:34:02.920
see the industry being
in, like, five, 10 years,

00:34:02.920 --> 00:34:04.582
given all this growth?

00:34:04.582 --> 00:34:06.040
DANIEL LANIGAN:
Well, the good news

00:34:06.040 --> 00:34:07.810
is that there's a
sort of proliferation

00:34:07.810 --> 00:34:10.510
of people that like to put
good things in their body.

00:34:10.510 --> 00:34:12.219
You know, if you had
told me 25 years ago

00:34:12.219 --> 00:34:14.343
that Whole Foods would be
as big as Whole Foods is,

00:34:14.343 --> 00:34:15.679
I would have said you're crazy.

00:34:15.679 --> 00:34:17.739
But I sort of
equate craft moving

00:34:17.739 --> 00:34:19.710
to sort of the Whole
Foods movement.

00:34:19.710 --> 00:34:23.650
This is not a perfect
analogy, but there's

00:34:23.650 --> 00:34:26.010
plenty of room for lots
of people to succeed.

00:34:26.010 --> 00:34:28.820
As I said, we're only
13% of the volume.

00:34:28.820 --> 00:34:31.340
So 13 out of 100 beers chosen
every day in the United States

00:34:31.340 --> 00:34:34.330
is craft beer.

00:34:34.330 --> 00:34:37.987
If For us to get
to 20%, let's say,

00:34:37.987 --> 00:34:40.570
that would mean every one of the
6,000 breweries in the United

00:34:40.570 --> 00:34:45.679
States would have to grow by 50%
in one year just to get to 20%.

00:34:45.679 --> 00:34:49.840
So there's a lot of
negative articles written

00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:51.928
about the bubble bursting
in the future of craft

00:34:51.928 --> 00:34:52.969
and it just slowing down.

00:34:52.969 --> 00:34:55.989
And I don't buy into that,
and I don't worry about that.

00:34:55.989 --> 00:34:57.390
If we do our jobs right--

00:34:57.390 --> 00:34:59.020
you know, we're
selling a lifestyle.

00:34:59.020 --> 00:35:00.020
We're selling happiness.

00:35:00.020 --> 00:35:01.810
And we're not just selling beer.

00:35:01.810 --> 00:35:05.247
We're selling the idea that beer
is the most affordable luxury

00:35:05.247 --> 00:35:05.830
item on Earth.

00:35:05.830 --> 00:35:07.030
There's value in this.

00:35:07.030 --> 00:35:10.330
Spend the extra couple
bucks on that four-pack Stop

00:35:10.330 --> 00:35:13.180
being a cheap person and
enjoy the value of it.

00:35:13.180 --> 00:35:15.040
And you don't get hung
over the next day.

00:35:15.040 --> 00:35:16.360
You feel better about yourself.

00:35:16.360 --> 00:35:20.360
You enjoy the experience
that much better.

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:23.380
It's an incredible thing
that we have right now.

00:35:23.380 --> 00:35:26.500
And the difference in price
between the 13% of beer

00:35:26.500 --> 00:35:28.190
in the world and the other 83%--

00:35:28.190 --> 00:35:30.010
I'm sorry, in the
United States--

00:35:30.010 --> 00:35:32.030
is not a lot of dough.

00:35:32.030 --> 00:35:35.650
I mean, we're happy to spend
$5 on a latte whatever.

00:35:38.314 --> 00:35:40.580
I'd rather spend $5 on
a good beer, you know?

00:35:40.580 --> 00:35:43.995
But most of the people
in this room can do both.

00:35:43.995 --> 00:35:45.370
So I'm not
particularly concerned

00:35:45.370 --> 00:35:46.946
about the future of craft.

00:35:46.946 --> 00:35:48.820
I am concerned about--
there's a lot of folks

00:35:48.820 --> 00:35:50.030
who are really
passionate about beer,

00:35:50.030 --> 00:35:50.880
they're passionate
about brewing,

00:35:50.880 --> 00:35:53.129
but they're not necessarily
passionate about business.

00:35:53.129 --> 00:35:54.670
And that's probably
where things are

00:35:54.670 --> 00:35:58.090
going to get a little murky,
because a lot of breweries

00:35:58.090 --> 00:36:00.970
don't have the right team, the
right advisors, the right tax

00:36:00.970 --> 00:36:03.930
people, the right accountants,
the right attorneys.

00:36:03.930 --> 00:36:04.831
They have bad leases.

00:36:04.831 --> 00:36:06.580
They don't have good
financial advisement.

00:36:06.580 --> 00:36:08.746
They don't have good
relationships with their banks.

00:36:08.746 --> 00:36:12.379
Like, that's the
real important stuff.

00:36:12.379 --> 00:36:13.920
There's a lot of
good beer out there.

00:36:13.920 --> 00:36:15.670
There's a lot of
bad beer out there.

00:36:15.670 --> 00:36:18.970
But there aren't a
lot of great teams.

00:36:18.970 --> 00:36:23.470
And that's more concern to
me than the proliferation

00:36:23.470 --> 00:36:26.050
of the number of breweries.

00:36:26.050 --> 00:36:29.470
I would say, though, if you
are planning a brewery now,

00:36:29.470 --> 00:36:30.565
you might be too late.

00:36:30.565 --> 00:36:31.905
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:31.905 --> 00:36:32.530
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:36:32.530 --> 00:36:34.037
Thank you.

00:36:34.037 --> 00:36:34.870
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:36:34.870 --> 00:36:36.790
So it seems like
you didn't really

00:36:36.790 --> 00:36:40.850
have much brewing experience
before you started the brewery.

00:36:40.850 --> 00:36:43.340
So like, how do you go
about making a beer?

00:36:43.340 --> 00:36:47.480
And especially if you don't have
experience, like, it seems--

00:36:47.480 --> 00:36:48.720
I don't know.

00:36:48.720 --> 00:36:50.240
Was it the people
that you hired?

00:36:50.240 --> 00:36:53.180
Or how did you just go
about finding a recipe

00:36:53.180 --> 00:36:55.270
and starting a brewery?

00:36:55.270 --> 00:36:57.809
And in terms of the
brewing actual beer.

00:36:57.809 --> 00:37:00.350
DANIEL LANIGAN: Yeah, so I've
never brewed a beer in my life,

00:37:00.350 --> 00:37:02.250
and now I never will, right?

00:37:02.250 --> 00:37:03.920
It's too late.

00:37:03.920 --> 00:37:06.920
I literally have never
home brewed a beer.

00:37:06.920 --> 00:37:09.760
I have, I think, a
relatively advanced palate.

00:37:09.760 --> 00:37:12.487
I taste everything
really thoughtfully

00:37:12.487 --> 00:37:14.570
and have really passionately
for many, many years,

00:37:14.570 --> 00:37:15.694
and written a lot of notes.

00:37:15.694 --> 00:37:18.980
And I would say I have a
relatively advanced palate,

00:37:18.980 --> 00:37:21.569
and that translates to wine
and food and coffee and all

00:37:21.569 --> 00:37:22.360
these other things.

00:37:22.360 --> 00:37:27.390
So I write the recipes a
little bit differently.

00:37:27.390 --> 00:37:32.840
I described the end result and
I hired really talented people.

00:37:32.840 --> 00:37:34.640
I had a couple of
idiot savants who

00:37:34.640 --> 00:37:38.420
are just geniuses when
it comes to brewing beer.

00:37:38.420 --> 00:37:40.610
And we were able to sit
down and talk about,

00:37:40.610 --> 00:37:42.410
what do we want this beer to be?

00:37:42.410 --> 00:37:46.710
And here's the 84
qualities of this beer.

00:37:46.710 --> 00:37:49.340
And it's sort of the backwards
way that most breweries do it,

00:37:49.340 --> 00:37:53.160
but it's sort of
creating the challenge

00:37:53.160 --> 00:37:55.280
and giving them the
answers to the questions,

00:37:55.280 --> 00:37:57.404
and letting them figure
out what the questions are.

00:37:57.404 --> 00:37:59.360
And that has been really
successful for us.

00:37:59.360 --> 00:38:02.810
It's been really rewarding to
sit down and write this stuff

00:38:02.810 --> 00:38:05.780
out and talk about it, and
two weeks later, have someone

00:38:05.780 --> 00:38:08.120
come to me and say, taste this.

00:38:08.120 --> 00:38:11.870
And to have 84% of it
be spot on and just

00:38:11.870 --> 00:38:14.240
have a couple of
tweaks to make, it's

00:38:14.240 --> 00:38:15.770
really a rewarding experience.

00:38:15.770 --> 00:38:17.450
But that's the way we do it.

00:38:17.450 --> 00:38:19.340
I went to brewing school.

00:38:19.340 --> 00:38:21.590
I got whatever
certificate you get

00:38:21.590 --> 00:38:23.340
for going to brewing school.

00:38:23.340 --> 00:38:24.680
But I never actually brewed.

00:38:24.680 --> 00:38:27.650
I have a general, basic idea
of the science behind it.

00:38:27.650 --> 00:38:30.020
But mostly, I'm just
talking about my vocabulary

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:33.110
was in line with the
vocabulary of my brewers.

00:38:33.110 --> 00:38:36.110
AUDIENCE: How do you look at the
trade-offs of kind of scaling

00:38:36.110 --> 00:38:37.880
distribution versus variety?

00:38:37.880 --> 00:38:40.280
You said you only have,
like, four beers right now.

00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:43.580
There's a lot of other
kind of hot areas

00:38:43.580 --> 00:38:46.010
that are growing
right now with sours

00:38:46.010 --> 00:38:49.010
and bourbon barrel-aged beers.

00:38:49.010 --> 00:38:50.720
So how do you look at that?

00:38:50.720 --> 00:38:51.560
DANIEL LANIGAN: Well, you
used the word growing.

00:38:51.560 --> 00:38:53.580
I'm not sure if
that's totally true.

00:38:53.580 --> 00:38:56.070
But for us, it's been
out of necessity.

00:38:56.070 --> 00:38:57.440
So we have a big facility.

00:38:57.440 --> 00:39:00.350
We have a limited
number of tanks.

00:39:00.350 --> 00:39:02.030
And every time we
ordered more tanks

00:39:02.030 --> 00:39:03.650
than we thought
we would need, we

00:39:03.650 --> 00:39:06.770
filled them with the same orders
from the same beers we had.

00:39:06.770 --> 00:39:11.720
So by design, we only have a
small amount of core beers,

00:39:11.720 --> 00:39:14.610
but we would have liked to
have had a couple more by now.

00:39:14.610 --> 00:39:15.860
We just didn't have the tanks.

00:39:15.860 --> 00:39:18.380
So tanks take six
months to make.

00:39:18.380 --> 00:39:21.230
We were cash flow
constrained for a while.

00:39:21.230 --> 00:39:23.690
We're not anymore,
which is great.

00:39:23.690 --> 00:39:27.140
But we've never had a
night in our whole history

00:39:27.140 --> 00:39:29.790
where we had a tank
that was empty.

00:39:29.790 --> 00:39:31.640
We fill them up and
then we sell them.

00:39:31.640 --> 00:39:34.970
And I would love to have
two or three more products.

00:39:34.970 --> 00:39:36.925
Not 10 or 12, but two
or three more by now.

00:39:36.925 --> 00:39:39.050
We just physically haven't--
we've had to make that

00:39:39.050 --> 00:39:39.550
decision.

00:39:39.550 --> 00:39:44.810
Like, we can short somebody in
Florida for a truckload of Boom

00:39:44.810 --> 00:39:48.110
Sauce and then have a truckload
of another beer to then spread

00:39:48.110 --> 00:39:50.140
out to our other territories.

00:39:50.140 --> 00:39:52.870
Just didn't think that was
a good business decision.

00:39:52.870 --> 00:39:54.879
And it's also
seasonality, timing.

00:39:54.879 --> 00:39:56.670
There's a lot of factors
that go into that.

00:39:56.670 --> 00:40:01.670
So ultimately, we're brewing
four new beers for 2018,

00:40:01.670 --> 00:40:07.260
and they'll broaden the
portfolio basically to eight.

00:40:07.260 --> 00:40:09.380
And then we have a
10-barrel system.

00:40:09.380 --> 00:40:12.350
So remember earlier I said that
we have a 40-barrel system,

00:40:12.350 --> 00:40:14.000
which is a monster.

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:16.220
So it's not an
experimental system.

00:40:16.220 --> 00:40:19.610
It's just too much beer to
produce to be messing around

00:40:19.610 --> 00:40:20.180
with things.

00:40:20.180 --> 00:40:22.310
So we got a 10-barrel
system, which

00:40:22.310 --> 00:40:25.700
is for our taproom, which we're
expanding after Christmas.

00:40:25.700 --> 00:40:28.810
We're building a
300-seat beer hall.

00:40:28.810 --> 00:40:31.250
And the 10-barrel will produce
beers that are available

00:40:31.250 --> 00:40:33.792
only in the taproom,
which'll give people

00:40:33.792 --> 00:40:35.000
more of a reason to go there.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.820
But that'll be sort of
our experimental system.

00:40:37.820 --> 00:40:39.600
So we have planned
for four more beers,

00:40:39.600 --> 00:40:41.580
and that'll bring us
to eight core beers.

00:40:41.580 --> 00:40:44.000
And then we'll have
sort of a rotational--

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:45.930
whatever of the five
or six or 10 beers

00:40:45.930 --> 00:40:48.460
we have in the taproom
that everyone loves,

00:40:48.460 --> 00:40:51.050
that'll help guide the
what's the next beer going

00:40:51.050 --> 00:40:52.414
to be question.

00:40:52.414 --> 00:40:55.080
But we're never going to have 30
beers in the market or anything

00:40:55.080 --> 00:40:59.690
like that, probably
because for us to go big

00:40:59.690 --> 00:41:05.210
when we launch a California
early next year, that's a very

00:41:05.210 --> 00:41:06.120
competitive market.

00:41:06.120 --> 00:41:07.190
It's kind of insane to go there.

00:41:07.190 --> 00:41:09.470
But it would be more insane
if we went there and asked

00:41:09.470 --> 00:41:11.660
every store owner to clear
off these three shelves

00:41:11.660 --> 00:41:14.420
and give us 15 SKUs here.

00:41:14.420 --> 00:41:18.320
It's a lot more appropriate and
approachable if we say, look.

00:41:18.320 --> 00:41:19.790
We have four beers.

00:41:19.790 --> 00:41:21.530
I just need this much space.

00:41:21.530 --> 00:41:25.010
Surely you can get rid of
your dog in the building

00:41:25.010 --> 00:41:26.660
and put four SKUs on the shelf.

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:29.809
So again, it's a little
bit by design as well.

00:41:29.809 --> 00:41:30.350
Thanks, guys.

00:41:30.350 --> 00:41:35.200
[APPLAUSE]

